Please join me in welcoming Jeremy.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
So let's start by talking about what a language model is.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:21.000
As you might have heard before, a language model is something that knows how to predict the next word of a sentence

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
or knows how to fill in the missing words of a sentence.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
We can look at an example of one. OpenAI has a language model, TextDaVinci003.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:39.000
We can play with it by passing in some words and ask it to predict what the next words might be.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
There's a nice site called nat.dev.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
nat.dev lets us play with a variety of language models.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Here I've selected TextDaVinci003 and I'll hit submit and it starts printing stuff out.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
The pandas were happily playing and eating the frogs that had fallen from the sky.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:04.000
It was an amazing sight to see these animals taking advantage of such a unique opportunity.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
The staff took quick measures to ensure the safety of the pandas and the frogs.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So there you go, that's what happened after the extraordinary rain of live frogs at the panda breeding facility.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:18.000
And each time then it'll give us a different result.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.000
And this is kind of fun.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Frogs perched on the heads of some of the pandas. It was an amazing sight, etc, etc.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:37.000
OK, so that's what a language model does.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Now you might notice here it hasn't predicted pandas, it's predicted panned.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And then separately, us.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
OK, after panned it's going to be us.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
So it's not always a whole word.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Here it's un- and then harmed.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Actually it's un-har-med.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
So you can see that it's not always predicting words.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Specifically what it's doing is predicting tokens.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:13.000
Tokens are either whole words or sub-word units, pieces of a word.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Or it could even be punctuation or numbers or so forth.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
So let's have a look at how that works.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
So, for example, we can use the actual...

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
It's called tokenization to create tokens from a string.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.000
We can use the same tokenizer that GPT uses by using TickToken.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And we can specifically say we want to use the same tokenizer that that model, TextEventually003, uses.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And so, for example, when I earlier tried this, it talked about the frog splashing.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
And so I thought, well, we'll encode they are splashing.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
And the result is a bunch of numbers.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:00.000
And what those numbers are, they're basically just lookups into a vocabulary that OpenAI, in this case, created.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And if you train your own models, you'll be automatically creating or your code will create.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:16.000
And if I then decode those, it says, oh, these numbers are they, space, are, space, spool, ashing.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
And so put that all together, they are splashing.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:29.000
So you can see that the start of a word is, with a space before it, is also being encoded here.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:36.000
So these language models are quite neat.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
They can work at all.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:46.000
But they're not, of themselves, really designed to do anything.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Let me explain.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:05:06.000
The basic idea of what ChatGPT, GPT-4, BARD, et cetera, are doing comes from a paper which describes an algorithm that I created back in 2017 called ULMfit.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And Sebastian Ruder and I wrote a paper up describing the ULMfit approach, which was the one that basically laid out what everybody's doing, how this system works.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.000
And the system has three steps.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Step one is language model training.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
But you'll see this is actually from the paper.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.000
We actually described it as pre-training.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Now, what language model pre-training does is this is the thing which predicts the next word of a sentence.

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:43.000
And so in the original ULMfit paper, so the algorithm I developed in 2017, then Sebastian Ruder and I wrote it up in 2018, early 2018.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
What I originally did was I trained this language model on Wikipedia.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:54.000
Now, what that meant is I took a neural network, and a neural network is just a function.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:59.000
If you don't know what it is, it's just a mathematical function that's extremely flexible, and it's got lots and lots of parameters.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
And initially, it can't do anything.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:09.000
But using stochastic gradient descent, or SGD, you can teach it to do almost anything if you give it examples.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
And so I gave it lots of examples of sentences from Wikipedia.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
So, for example, from the Wikipedia article for the birds.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:24.000
The birds is a 1963 American natural horror thriller film produced and directed by Alfred, and then it would stop.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.000
And so then the model would have to guess what the next word is.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:32.000
And if it guessed Hitchcock, it would be rewarded.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And if it guessed something else, it would be penalized.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
And effectively, basically, it's trying to maximize those rewards.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:45.000
It's trying to find a set of weights for this function that makes it more likely that it would predict Hitchcock.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:54.000
To do a good job of solving this problem as well as possible, of guessing the next word of sentences,

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:02.000
the neural network is going to have to learn a lot of stuff about the world.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:11.000
It's going to learn that there are things called objects, that there's a thing called time, that objects react to each other over time.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:18.000
That there are things called movies, that movies have directors, that there are people, that people have names and so forth.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:26.000
And that a movie director is Alfred Hitchcock and he directed horror films and so on and so forth.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:33.000
It's going to have to learn an extraordinary amount if it's going to do a really good job of predicting the next word of sentences.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Now, these neural networks specifically are deep neural networks.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.000
This is deep learning.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And in these deep neural networks, which have, when I created this, I think it had like 100 million parameters.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Nowadays, they have billions of parameters.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:02.000
It's got the ability to create a rich hierarchy of abstractions and representations, which it can build on.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:10.000
And so this is really the key idea behind neural networks and language models.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:17.000
It's that if it's going to do a good job of being able to predict the next word of any sentence in any situation,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
it's going to have to know an awful lot about the world.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:31.000
It's going to have to know about how to solve math questions or figure out the next move in a chess game or recognize poetry and so on and so forth.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.000
Now, nobody said it's going to do a good job of that.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:41.000
So it's a lot of work to create and train a model that is good at that.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:52.000
But if you can create one that's good at that, it's going to have a lot of capabilities internally that it would have to be drawing on to be able to do this effectively.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So the key idea here for me is that this is a form of compression.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:05.000
And this idea of the relationship between compression and intelligence goes back many, many decades.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And the basic idea is that, yeah, if you can guess what words are coming up next,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:20.000
then effectively you're compressing all that information down into a neural network.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
Now, I said this is not useful of itself.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
Well, why do we do it?

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:28.000
Well, we do it because we want to pull out those capabilities.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:32.000
And the way we pull out those capabilities is we take two more steps.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
The second step is we do something called language model fine tuning.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:42.000
And in language model fine tuning, we are no longer just giving it all of Wikipedia.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Or nowadays, we don't just give it all of Wikipedia.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:51.000
But in fact, a large chunk of the Internet is fed to pre-training these models.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:10:01.000
In the fine tuning stage, we feed it a set of documents a lot closer to the final task that we want the model to do.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:08.000
But it's still the same basic idea. It's still trying to predict the next word of a sentence.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.000
After that, we then do a final classifier fine tuning.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:18.000
And in the classifier fine tuning, this is the kind of end task we're trying to get it to do.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
Now, nowadays, these two steps are very specific approaches are taken.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
For the step two, the step B, the language model fine tuning,

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
people nowadays do a particular kind called instruction tuning.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:40.000
The idea is that the task we want most of the time to achieve is solve problems, answer questions.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:45.000
And so in the instruction tuning phase, we use data sets like this one.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:51.000
This is a great data set called OpenOrca created by a fantastic open source group.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And it's built on top of something called the Flan collection.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:03.000
And you can see that basically there's all kinds of different questions in here.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:09.000
So there's four gigabytes of questions.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Here are some examples of instructions.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
I think this is from the Flan data set, if I remember correctly.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
So, for instance, it could be, does the sentence in the Iron Age answer the question,

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.000
the period of time from 1200 to 1000 BCE is known as what?

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Choice is one, yes or no.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And then the language model is meant to write one or two as appropriate for yes or no.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
So it's still doing language modeling.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:42.000
So fine tuning and pre-training are kind of the same thing.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:51.000
But this is more targeted now, not just to be able to fill in the missing parts of any document from the Internet,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:58.000
but to fill in the words necessary to answer questions, to do useful things.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:02.000
OK, so that's instruction tuning.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:05.000
And then step three, which is the classifier fine tuning.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:11.000
Nowadays, there's generally various approaches, such as reinforcement learning from human feedback and others,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:22.000
which are basically giving humans or sometimes more advanced models,

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:28.000
multiple answers to a question such as here are some from a reinforcement learning from human feedback paper.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:33.000
I can't remember which one I got it from. List five ideas for how to regain enthusiasm for my career.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:40.000
And so the model will spit out two possible answers or it will have a less good model and more good model.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:45.000
And then a human or a better model will pick which is best.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:51.000
And so that's used for the final fine tuning stage.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:55.000
OK, so when we talk about a language model,

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
we could be talking about something that's just been pre-trained,

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:04.000
something that's been fine tuned or something that's gone through something like RLHF.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:11.000
All of those things are generally described nowadays as language models.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So my view is that if you are going to be good at language modelling in any way,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
then you need to start by being a really effective user of language models.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
And to be a really effective user of language models, you've got to use the best one that there is.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
And currently, so what are we up to? September 2023.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
The best one is by far GPT-4.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:41.000
This might change sometime in the not too distant future, but this is right now.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:44.000
GPT-4 is the recommendation, strong, strong recommendation.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Now, you can use GPT-4 by paying 20 bucks a month to open AI and then you can use it a whole lot.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:59.000
It's very hard to run out of credits, I find.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
Now, what can GPT-2?

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
It's interesting and instructive, in my opinion,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:11.000
to start with the very common views you see on the Internet or even in academia about what it can't do.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:17.000
So, for example, there was this paper you might have seen, GPT-4 can't reason,

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:26.000
which describes a number of empirical analysis done of 25 diverse reasoning problems

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
and found that it was not able to solve them.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:33.000
It's utterly incapable of reasoning.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:38.000
So I always find you've got to be a bit careful about reading stuff like this,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:48.000
because I just took the first three that I came across in that paper and I gave them to GPT-4.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:57.000
And by the way, something very useful in GPT-4 is you can click on the share button

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
and you'll get something that looks like this.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
And this is really handy.

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So here's an example of something from the paper that said GPT-4 can't do this.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
Mabel's heart rate at 9 a.m. was 75 beats per minute.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.000
Her blood pressure at 7 p.m. was 120 over 80.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.000
She died 11 p.m.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
Was she alive at noon?

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Of course, she's a human.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
We know, obviously, she must be.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:27.000
And GPT-4 says, hmm, this appears to be a riddle, not a real inquiry into medical conditions.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
Here's a summary of the information.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:35.000
And, yeah, it sounds like Mabel was alive at noon.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:36.000
So that's correct.

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:41.000
This was the second one I tried from the paper that says GPT-4 can't do this.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.000
And I found actually GPT-4 can do this.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:48.000
And it said that GPT-4 can't do this.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
And I found GPT-4 can do this.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:57.000
Now, I mention this to say GPT-4 is probably a lot better than you would expect

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:04.000
if you've read all this stuff on the internet about all the dumb things that it does.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Almost every time I see on the internet saying something that GPT-4 can't do, I check it and it turns out it does.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
This one was just last week.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Sally, a girl, has three brothers.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
Each brother has two sisters.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
How many sisters does Sally have?

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:25.000
So I have to think about it.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And so GPT-4 says, OK, Sally is counted as one sister by each of her brothers.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:37.000
If each brother has two sisters, that means there's another sister in the picture apart from Sally.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
So Sally has one sister.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Correct.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Why is it that people are claiming that GPT-4 can't do these things?

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:57.000
Well, the reason is because I think on the whole they are not aware of how GPT-4 was trained.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:04.000
GPT-4 was not trained at any point to give correct answers.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:11.000
GPT-4 was trained initially to give most likely next words.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:17.000
And there's an awful lot of stuff on the internet where documents are not describing things that are true.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
There could be fiction. There could be jokes.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.000
There could be just stupid people saying dumb stuff.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:28.000
So this first stage does not necessarily give you correct answers.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:36.000
The second stage with the instruction tuning, also, it's trying to give correct answers.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:43.000
But part of the problem is that then in the stage where you start asking people which answer do they like better,

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:52.000
people tended to say in these things that they prefer more confident answers.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.000
And they often were not people who were trained well enough to recognize wrong answers.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:06.000
So there's lots of reasons that the SGD weight updates from this process for stuff like GPT-4

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:12.000
don't particularly or don't entirely reward correct answers.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
But you can help it want to give you correct answers.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:24.000
If you think about the LM pre-training, what are the kinds of things in a document that would suggest,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
oh, this is going to be high quality information.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And so you can actually prime GPT-4 to give you high quality information by giving it custom instructions.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:45.000
And what this does is this is basically text that is prepended to all of your queries.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And so you say like, oh, you're brilliant at reasoning.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:55.000
So like, OK, that's obviously you have to prime it to give good answers.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:05.000
And then try to work against the fact that the RLHF folks preferred confidence.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:10.000
Just tell it. No, tell me if there might not be a correct answer.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:17.000
Also, the way that the text is generated is it literally generates the next word.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:22.000
And then it puts all that whole lot back into the model and generates the next, next word,

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:27.000
puts that all back in the model, generates the next, next, next word, and so forth.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:31.000
That means the more words it generates, the more computation it can do.

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And so I literally, I tell it that.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Right. And so I say first spend a few sentences explaining background context, et cetera.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:53.000
So this custom instruction allows it to solve more challenging problems.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:58.000
And you can see the difference. Here's what it looks like.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:03.000
For example, if I say, how do I get a count of rows grouped by value in pandas?

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:08.000
And it just gives me a whole lot of information, which is actually it thinking.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
So I just skip over it and that gives me the answer.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:21.000
And actually in my custom instructions, I actually say if the request begins with VV,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
actually make it as concise as possible.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:28.000
And so it kind of goes into brief mode. And here is brief mode.

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:31.000
How do I get the group? This is the same thing, but with VV at the start.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And it just spits it out. Now, in this case, it's a really simple question.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:38.000
So I didn't need time to think.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:46.000
So hopefully that gives you a sense of how to get language models to give good answers.

00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:52.000
You have to help them. And if you, if it's not working, it might be user error, basically.

00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:59.000
But having said that, there's plenty of stuff that language models like GPT-4 can't do.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:04.000
One thing to think carefully about is, does it know about itself?

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:09.000
Can you ask it, what is your context length? How were you trained?

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.000
What transformer architecture are you based on?

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:20.000
At any one of these stages, did it have the opportunity to learn any of those things?

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:22.000
Well, obviously not at the pre-training stage.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:30.000
Nothing on the Internet existed during GPT-4's training saying how GPT-4 was trained.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:34.000
Probably ditto in the instruction tuning, probably ditto in the RLHF.

00:21:34.000 --> 00:21:40.000
So in general, you can't ask, for example, a language model about itself.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:46.000
Now, again, because of the RLHF, it'll want to make you happy by giving you opinionated answers.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:53.000
So it'll just spit out the most likely thing it thinks with great confidence.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.000
This is just a general kind of hallucination, right?

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:01.000
So hallucinations is just this idea that the language model wants to complete the sentence

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:07.000
and it wants to do it in an opinionated way that's likely to make people happy.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:12.000
It doesn't know anything about URLs. It really hasn't seen many at all.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:16.000
I think a lot of them, if not all of them, pretty much were stripped out.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:24.000
So if you ask it anything about, like, what's at this web page, again, it'll generally just make it up.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:29.000
And it doesn't know, at least GPT-4 doesn't know anything after September 2021

00:22:29.000 --> 00:22:38.000
because the information it was pre-trained on was from that time period, September 2021 and before,

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:41.000
called the knowledge cutoff.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:52.000
OK, now something else super helpful that you can use is what they call advanced data analysis.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:23:03.000
In advanced data analysis, you can ask it to basically write code for you.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.000
And we're going to look at how to implement this from scratch ourself quite soon.

00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:09.000
But first of all, let's learn how to use it.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:17.000
So I was trying to build something that split into markdown headings, a document on third level markdown headings.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:21.000
So that's three hashes at the start of a line.

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:26.000
And I was doing it on the whole of Wikipedia. So using regular expressions was really slow.

00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:29.000
So I said, oh, I want to speed this up.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:37.000
And it said, OK, here's some code, which is great because then I can say, OK, test it and include edge cases.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:46.000
And so it then puts in the code, creates edge cases, tests it.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:51.000
And it says, yep, it's working.

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:56.000
However, I discovered it's not. I noticed it's actually removing the carriage return at the end of each sentence.

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:00.000
So I said, oh, fix that and update your tests.

00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:03.000
So it said, OK.

00:24:03.000 --> 00:24:10.000
So now it's changed the test, updated the test cases. Let's run them. And oh, it's not working.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:15.000
So it says, oh yeah, fix the issue in the test cases.

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:23.000
No, that didn't work. And you can see it's quite clever the way it's trying to fix it by looking at the results.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.000
But as you can see, it's not.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:33.000
Every one of these is another attempt, another attempt, another attempt until eventually I gave up waiting.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:37.000
And it's so funny each time it's like debugging again.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:43.000
OK, this time I've got to handle it properly. And I gave up at the point where it's like, oh, one more attempt.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.000
So it didn't solve it, interestingly enough.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:56.000
And, you know, again, there's some limits to the amount of kind of logic that it can do.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:00.000
This is really a very simple question. I asked it to do for me.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:08.000
And so hopefully you can see you can't expect even GPT-4 code interpreter or advanced data analysis, as it's now called,

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:13.000
to make it so you don't have to write code anymore.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:18.000
You know, it's not a substitute for having programmers.

00:25:18.000 --> 00:25:20.000
So.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:25.000
Why would you use the OpenAI API rather than ChatGPT?

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:27.000
Because you can do it programmatically.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:36.000
So you can, you know, you can analyze data sets, you can do repetitive stuff.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.000
It's kind of like a different way of programming.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:43.000
You know, it's things that you can think of describing.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:46.000
But let's just look at the most simple example of what that looks like.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:53.000
So if you pip install OpenAI, then you can import ChatCompletion.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:59.000
And then you can say, OK, ChatCompletion.create using GPT 3.5 Turbo.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
And then you can pass in a system message.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
This is basically the same as custom instructions.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.000
So, OK, you're an Aussie LLM that uses Aussie slang and analogies wherever possible.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:10.000
OK.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And so you can see I'm passing in an array here of messages.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:19.000
So the first is the system message and then the user message, which is, what is money?

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:20.000
OK.

00:26:20.000 --> 00:26:27.000
So GPT 3.5 returns a big embedded dictionary.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:36.000
And the message content is, well, my money is like the oil that keeps the machinery of our economy running smoothly.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:37.000
There you go.

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:42.000
Just like a koala loves its eucalyptus leaves, we humans can't survive without this stuff.

00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:47.000
So there's the Aussie LLM's view of what is money.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:58.000
Now, what happens when we are, this is really important to understand, when we have a follow up in the same conversation?

00:26:58.000 --> 00:26:59.000
How does that work?

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.000
So we just asked what GOAT means.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:13.000
So, for example, Michael Jordan is often referred to as the GOAT for his exceptional skills and accomplishments.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:18.000
And Elvis and the Beatles are referred to as GOAT due to their profound influence and achievement.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:23.000
So I could say.

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:31.000
What profound influence and achievements are you referring to?

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:34.000
OK, well, I meant Elvis Presley and the Beatles did all these things.

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:35.000
Now, how does that work?

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:37.000
How does this follow up work?

00:27:37.000 --> 00:27:43.000
Well, what happens is the entire conversation is passed back.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
And so we can actually do that here.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:49.000
So here is the same system prompt.

00:27:49.000 --> 00:27:52.000
Here is the same question.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
Right. And then the answer comes back with role assistant.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
And I'm going to do something pretty cheeky.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:03.000
I'm going to pretend that it didn't say money is like oil.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:08.000
I'm going to say, oh, you actually said money is like kangaroos.

00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:10.000
I thought, what is it going to do?

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:16.000
OK, so you can like literally invent a conversation in which the language model said something different.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:20.000
Because this is actually how it's done in a multistage conversation.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
There's no state.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
Right. There's nothing stored on the server.

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:30.000
You're passing back the entire conversation again and telling it what it told you.

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:34.000
Right. So I'm going to tell it it's it told me that money is like kangaroos.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:37.000
And then I'll ask the user, oh, really? In what way?

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:44.000
And it's kind of cool because you can like see how it convinces you of of something I just invented.

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.000
Oh, let me break it down for you.

00:28:46.000 --> 00:28:49.000
But just like kangaroos hop around and carry their joeys in their pouch.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:51.000
Money is a means of carrying value around.

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:56.000
So there you go. It's make your own analogy.

00:28:56.000 --> 00:28:58.000
So what else can we do?

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Well, let's create our own code interpreter that runs inside Jupyter.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:11.000
And so to do this, we're going to take advantage of a really nifty thing called function calling,

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:14.000
which is provided by the OpenAI API.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:21.000
And in function calling, when we call our askGPT function, which is this little one here,

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:28.000
we had room to pass in some keyword arguments that would be just passed along to check completion dot create.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:33.000
And one of those keyword arguments you can pass is.

00:29:33.000 --> 00:29:36.000
Functions. What on earth is that?

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:45.000
Functions tells OpenAI about tools that you have, about functions that you have.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:29:51.000
So, for example, I created a really simple function called sums.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:56.000
And it adds two things.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:00.000
In fact, it adds two ints.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:08.000
And I am going to pass that function to check completion dot create.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:12.000
Now, you can't pass a Python function directly.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:16.000
You actually have to pass what's called the JSON schema.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:19.000
So you have to pass the schema for the function.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:31.000
So I created this nifty little function that you're welcome to borrow, which uses Pydantic and also Python's inspect module

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:38.000
to automatically take a Python function and return the schema for it.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:41.000
And so this is actually what's going to get passed to OpenAI.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:44.000
It's going to know that there's a function called sums, it's going to know what it does,

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:52.000
and it's going to know what parameters it takes, what the defaults are, and what's required.

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.000
So this is like, when I first heard about this, I found this a bit mind bending,

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:00.000
because this is so different to how we normally program computers.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:05.000
The key thing for programming the computer here actually is the docstring.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:10.000
This is the thing that GPT-4 will look at and say, oh, what does this function do?

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.000
So it's critical that this describes exactly what the function does.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And so if I then say, what is 6 plus 3?

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:26.000
And I just really wanted to make sure it actually did it here.

00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:32.000
So I gave it lots of prompts to say, because obviously it knows how to do it itself without calling sums.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:38.000
So it'll only use your functions if it feels it needs to, which is a weird concept.

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
I mean, I guess feels is not a great word to use,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:47.000
but you kind of have to anthropomorphize these things a little bit because they don't behave like normal computer programs.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:55.000
So if I ask GPT, what is 6 plus 3, and tell it that there's a function called sums,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:59.000
then it does not actually return the number 9.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:03.000
Instead, it returns something saying, please call a function.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:08.000
Call this function and pass it these arguments.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.000
So if I print it out, there's the arguments.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:21.000
And so if I now say, OK, call the function that we got back, we finally get 9.

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:24.000
So this is a very simple example.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:26.000
It's not really doing anything that useful.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:34.000
But what we could do now is we can create a much more powerful function called Python.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:45.000
And the Python function executes code using Python and returns the result.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:53.000
So now I can say, ask GPT, what is 12 factorial?

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:59.000
System prompt, you can use Python for any required computations and say, OK, here's a function you've got available.

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:04.000
It's the Python function.

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:12.000
So if I now call this, it will pass me back again a completion object.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:19.000
And here it's going to say, OK, I want you to call Python passing in this argument.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:25.000
And when I do, it's going to go import math, result equals blah, and then return result.

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:29.000
Do I want to do that? Yes, I do.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.000
And there it is.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:35.000
Now, there's one more step which we can optionally do.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:40.000
I mean, we've got the answer we wanted, but often we want the answer in more of a chat format.

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:48.000
And so the way to do that is to, again, repeat everything that you've passed into so far.

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:56.000
But then instead of adding an assistant role response, we have to provide a function role response.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:02.000
And simply put in here the result we got back from the function.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:10.000
And if we do that, we now get the prose response.

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:16.000
12 factorial is equal to 471,001,600.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Now, functions like Python, you can still ask it about non-Python things.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:30.000
And it just ignores it if you don't need it.

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:43.000
So you can have a whole bunch of functions available that you've built to do whatever you need for the stuff which the language model isn't familiar with.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:54.000
And it'll still solve whatever it can on its own and use your tools, use your functions where possible.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:35:01.000
OK, so we have built our own code interpreter from scratch.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:04.000
I think that's pretty amazing.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:14.000
So that is what you can do with some of the stuff you can do with OpenAI.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:18.000
What about stuff that you can do on your own computer?

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:23.000
So then what we're going to be using is a library called Transformers from HuggingFace.

00:35:23.000 --> 00:35:32.000
And the reason for that is that basically people upload lots of pre-trained models or fine-tuned models up to the HuggingFace hub.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:40.000
And in fact, there's even a leaderboard where you can see which are the best models.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:47.000
All right, so you can find models to try out from things like this leaderboard.

00:35:47.000 --> 00:36:01.000
And there's also a really great leaderboard called FastEval, which I like a lot, because it focuses on some more sophisticated evaluation methods, such as this chain of thought evaluation method.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:04.000
So I kind of trust these a little bit more.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:13.000
And these are also, you know, GSM 8K is a difficult math benchmark, BigBench Hard, and so forth.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:25.000
So, yeah, so, you know, StableBeluga2, WizardMath13B, DolphinLima13B, etc. These would all be good options.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Yeah, so you need to pick a model. And at the moment, nearly all the good models are based on Meta's Lama2.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
So when I say based on, what does that mean?

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:42.000
Well, what that means is this model here, Lama2-7B.

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:46.000
So it's a Lama model. That's just the name Meta called it.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
This is their version 2 of Lama.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:52.000
This is their 7 billion size one. It's the smallest one that they make.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:58.000
And specifically, these weights have been created for HuggingFace, so you can load it with the HuggingFace transformers.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:04.000
And this model has only got as far as here. It's done the language model for pre-training.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:11.000
It's done none of the instruction tuning and none of the RLHF.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:17.000
So we would need to fine tune it to really get it to do much useful.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:25.000
So we can just say, OK, automatically create the appropriate model for language model.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:32.000
So causal LM basically refers to that ULM fit stage 1 process or stage 2, in fact.

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:37.000
So get the pre-trained model from this name, Meta Lama Lama2, etc.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:50.000
OK. Now, generally speaking, we use 16 bit floating point numbers nowadays.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:54.000
But if you think about it, 16 bit is 2 bytes.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:03.000
So 7B times 2, it's going to be 14 gigabytes just to load in the weights.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:08.000
So you've got to have a decent model to be able to do that.

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:16.000
Perhaps surprisingly, you can actually just cast it to 8 bit and it still works pretty well, thanks to something called discretization.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:19.000
So let's try that.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:22.000
So remember, this is just a language model that can only complete sentences.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:25.000
We can't ask it a question and expect a great answer.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:29.000
So let's just give it the start of a sentence. Jeremy Howard is R.

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:34.000
And so we need the right tokenizer, so this will automatically create the right kind of tokenizer for this model.

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:38.000
We can grab the tokens as PyTorch.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:43.000
Here they are.

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:45.000
And.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:52.000
Just to confirm, if we decode them back again, we get back the original plus a special token to say this is the start of a document.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:55.000
And so we can now call generate.

00:38:55.000 --> 00:39:10.000
So generate will autoregressively, so call the model again and again, passing its previous result back as the next as the next input.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:13.000
And I'm just going to do that 15 times.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:16.000
So this is you can you can write this for loop yourself.

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:17.000
This isn't doing anything fancy.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:26.000
In fact, I would recommend writing this yourself to make sure that you know how that it all works OK.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:29.000
We have to put those tokens on the GPU.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:32.000
And at the end, I recommend putting them back onto the CPU, the result.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.000
And here are the tokens. Not very interesting.

00:39:35.000 --> 00:39:38.000
So we have to decode them using the tokenizer.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:45.000
And so the first 25, sorry, first 15 tokens are Jeremy Howard Izhar, 28 year old Australian AI researcher and entrepreneur.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:50.000
OK, well, 28 years old is not exactly correct, but we'll call it close enough.

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
I like that. Thank you very much.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.000
Llama7b.

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:59.000
So, OK, so we've got a language model completing sentences.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:01.000
It took.

00:40:01.000 --> 00:40:04.000
One and a third seconds.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:08.000
And that's a bit slower than it could be because we used 8-bit.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:21.000
If we use 16-bit, there's a special thing called bfloat16, which is a really great 16-bit floating point format that's usable on any somewhat recent NVIDIA GPU.

00:40:21.000 --> 00:40:26.000
Now, if we use it, it's going to take twice as much RAM as we discussed.

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.000
But look at the time.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:33.000
It's come down to 390 milliseconds.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:37.000
Now, there is a better option still than even that.

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:54.000
There's a different kind of discretization called GPTQ, where a model is carefully optimized to work with 4 or 8 or other, you know, lower precision data automatically.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:41:09.000
And this particular person, known as The Bloke, is fantastic at taking popular models, running that optimization process, and then uploading the results back to Hackingface.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:14.000
So we can use this GPTQ version.

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:19.000
And internally, this is actually going to use, I'm not sure exactly how many bits this particular one is.

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:21.000
I think it's probably going to be 4 bits.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:23.000
But it's going to be much more optimized.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:25.000
And so look at this.

00:41:25.000 --> 00:41:26.000
270 milliseconds.

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:31.000
It's actually faster than 16-bit.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:36.000
Even though internally it's actually casting it up to 16-bit each layer to do it.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:39.000
And that's because there's a lot less memory moving around.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:45.000
And to confirm, in fact, what we can even do now is we can go up to 13-bit.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:46.000
Easy.

