So you can see we've got our own models giving us some pretty good information.

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
How do we make it even better?

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:17.000
You know, because it's still hallucinating, you know.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:24.000
And, you know, LLAMA2, I think, has been trained with more up-to-date information than GPT4.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:29.000
It doesn't have the September 2021 cutoff.

00:46:29.000 --> 00:46:32.000
But, you know, it's still got a knowledge cutoff.

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:35.000
You know, we would like to be able to use the most up-to-date information.

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:40.000
We want to use the right information to answer these questions as well as possible.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:45.000
So to do this, we can use something called Retrieval Augmented Generation.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:55.000
So what happens with Retrieval Augmented Generation is when we take the question we've been asked, like,

00:46:55.000 --> 00:46:56.000
Who is Jeremy Howard?

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:07.000
And then we say, okay, let's try and search for documents that may help us answer that question.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:11.000
So obviously, we would expect, for example, Wikipedia to be useful.

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:28.000
And then what we do is we say, okay, with that information, let's now see if we can tell the language model about what we found and then have it answer the question.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:29.000
So let me show you.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:36.000
So let's actually grab a Wikipedia Python package.

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:42.000
We will scrape Wikipedia, grabbing the Jeremy Howard web page.

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:48.000
And so here's the start of the Jeremy Howard Wikipedia page.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.000
It has 613 words.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:56.000
Now, generally speaking, these open source models will have a context length of about 2000 or 4000.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:59.000
So the context length is how many tokens can it handle.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:00.000
So that's fine.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
It'll be able to handle this web page.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:05.000
And what we're going to do is we're going to ask it the question.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:08.000
So we're going to have here a question and with a question.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:11.000
But before it, we're going to say answer the question with the help of the context.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:13.000
We're going to provide this to the language model.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:15.000
And we're going to say context.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:17.000
And they're going to have the whole web page.

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.000
So suddenly now our question is going to be a lot bigger.

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.000
Our prompt.

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:23.000
Right.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:33.000
So our prompt now contains the entire web page, the whole Wikipedia page, followed by a question.

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:47.000
And so now it says, Jeremy Howard is an Australian data scientist, entrepreneur and educator, known for his work in deep learning, co-founder of Fast.ai, teaches courses, develops software, conducts research, used to be.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:48.000
Yeah.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:49.000
OK.

00:48:49.000 --> 00:48:50.000
It's perfect.

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:51.000
Right.

00:48:51.000 --> 00:48:53.000
So it's actually done a really good job.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:03.000
Like if somebody asked me to send them a, you know, 100 word bio, that would actually probably be better than I would have written myself.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:10.000
And you'll see, even though I asked for 300 tokens, it actually got sent back the end of stream token.

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:16.000
And so it knows to stop at this point.

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:22.000
Well, that's all very well, but how do we know to pass in the Jeremy Howard Wikipedia page?

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:37.000
Well, the way we know which Wikipedia page to pass in is that we can use another model to tell us which web page or which document is the most useful for answering a question.

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:58.000
And the way we do that is we can use something called sentence transformer and we can use a special kind of model that's specifically designed to take a document and turn it into a bunch of activations where two documents that are similar will have similar activations.

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
So let me just let me show you what I mean.

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:11.000
What I'm going to do is I'm going to grab just the first paragraph of my Wikipedia page and I'm going to grab the first paragraph of Tony Blair's Wikipedia page.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
OK, so we're pretty different people.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:16.000
Right. This is just like a really simple, small example.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:33.000
And I'm going to then call this model, I'm going to say encode, and I'm going to encode my Wikipedia first paragraph, Tony Blair's first paragraph, and the question, which was, who is Jeremy Howard?

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:45.000
And it's going to pass back a 384 long vector of embeddings for the question, for me, and for Tony Blair.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:54.000
And what I can now do is I can calculate the similarity between the question and the Jeremy Howard Wikipedia page.

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:59.000
And I can also do it for the question versus the Tony Blair Wikipedia page.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:16.000
And as you can see, it's higher for me. And so that tells you that if you're trying to figure out what document to use to help you answer this question, better off using the Jeremy Howard Wikipedia page than the Tony Blair Wikipedia page.

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:33.000
So if you had a few hundred documents you were thinking of using to give back to the model as context to help it answer a question, you could literally just pass them all through to encode, go through each one, one at a time, and see which is closest.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:48.000
When you've got thousands or millions of documents, you can use something called a vector database, where basically as a one-off thing, you go through and you encode all of your documents.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:57.000
And so in fact, there's lots of pre-built systems for this. Here's an example of one called H2O-GPT.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:10.000
And this is just something that I've got running here on my computer. It's just an open source thing written in Python, sitting here running on port 7860.

